huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
The Fish Lake unit is a general season hunt unit and is managed to provide deer hunting opportunity. The unit is excellent deer habitat and is a popular place to hunt. In recent years the unit has experienced small decreas in the deer population and in the buck/doe ratio. Deer hunting has been good. Though not managed as a trophy unit, hunters have been noticing good numbers of mature bucks.

Deer populate the entire unit and can move in response to hunting pressure and weather. Elevations range from 5,000 ft valleys to peaks over 11,000 ft. Vegetation communities range from sagebrush, pinyon/juniper, to aspen/conifer.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: This is a large area and cellular phone coverage is very spotty on this hunt unit.  Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for hot & dry, or rainy, lightening, windy or even snowy conditions.  Early snow storms sometimes occur during this hunt.  Most of the time snow will melt off within a day or so.  Be prepared for muddy or snowy road conditions.  During the archery season hunters should be prepared to cool harvested game quickly due to warm temperatures.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
The Fish Lake unit is a general season hunt unit and is managed to provide deer hunting opportunity. The unit is excellent deer habitat and is a popular place to hunt. In recent years the unit has experienced a decrease in the deer population and in the buck/doe ratio. Deer hunting has been good. Though not managed as a trophy unit, hunters have been noticing an increased number of mature bucks.

Deer populate the entire unit and can move in response to hunting pressure and weather. Elevations range from 5,000 ft valleys to peaks over 11,000 ft. Vegetation communities range from sagebrush, pinyon/juniper, to aspen/conifer.

Limited Entry Muzzleloader Season: In late October and early November the deer on the Fish Lake unit tend to be very spread out. On much of the unit some of the deer have moved onto or near their winter range. Snow levels permitting, there are also some deer on the highest peaks. Hunters should use scouting just prior to the season to locate deer concentrations. Hunters often concentrate in areas where deer are easily seen near agricultural areas.

Migration Patterns: Some of the deer on Fish Lake unit begin to migrate to or closer to their winter range in mid-October. By the time this early November hunt arrives a sizable portion of the herd is often in the transitional ranges between their winter and summer ranges. However many deer also stay as high as they can until heavy snows push them lower. Most of the migration is rather simple, the deer just move up or down in elevation. However there are some deer that move from their summering areas on the north and central parts of the unit to the southern, eastern, and western parts of the unit closer to their winter range.

Mule Deer Rut: The mule deer rut usually runs from mid Nov.-mid December. For this hunt expect bucks to be just beginning to rut. Many of the bucks will be with the does but some will not.

Recommended Areas to Hunt on the Fish Lake Unit: There are deer spread across the entire Fish Lake unit. During the archery and muzzleloader hunts concentrate in areas above 8,000 ft. During the any-weapon hunt the deer are spread from the top of the mountain to the valley floors. During this early November muzzleloader hunt the deer will be very spread out unless there have been significant snow storms. Every year a few older age class bucks are taken. There is no single area that produces more than others. The key is to scout your areas before the hunt to look for the deer you want. If deer numbers are not significant at you elevation try lower or high elevations depending on the snow.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The majority of the land within the unit is owned by the USFS and the BLM and is open to the public. There are some large tracts of private land, many of which are enrolled in the CWMU program and you must possess a valid CWMU permit to hunt big game there. Permission by landowner may be granted by to hunt cougars on the CWMUs
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are many improved Camping areas on the Fish Lake unit, both public and private. Good camping exists in Gooseberry area, Elk Horn, multiple areas around Fish Lake and Johnson Reservoir. Primitive camping is allowed on much of the BLM and USFS managed lands. There is one improved campground managed by the Piute tribe near Koosharem reservoir. Contact the managing agency for detailed information. http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/richfield.html
http://www.fs.usda.gov/activity/fishlake/recreation/camping-cabins
http://www.recreation.gov/unifSearchResults.do
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: There are many ways to access this unit. The north end can be accessed off of I-70 at the Gooseberry exit and also at the Hwy 72 exit. There are also many smaller unimproved roads that get you into good country from the frontage road along I-70. Access to the eastern side of the unit is via hwy 72. Roads that fork from hwy 72 that get you into good county include the Last Chance road, Road #206 that gets you onto the Thousand Lake Mountain, road #036 that takes you past Mill Meadow Reservoir and to Fish Lake.  There are many ATV trails and smaller unimproved roads that fork off of Hwy 72. The main access on the south end is SR-25 to Fish Lake via SR-24.   The west side is accessed via several dirt roads including the Hancock Flat road off of SR-25,  Road #053 that forks off of SR-24 gets you into the Rex Reservoir, and the Lost Creek country.
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS 1:100,000 Maps Loa, Salina.  USFS Travel Management Map
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: There is an expansive road and trail system on this unit. All roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the BLM, USFS, Sevier and Wayne counties. Most travel regulations are covered in their Travel Management Plans.  Please direct questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated to the Fish Lake National Forest, Richfield and Loa offices. BLM offices are in Richfield and Loa. The USFS has a travel map that covers most of this area.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: Private/Tribal Lands issues: There are several large tracts of private property on this unit. Several of these tracts are enrolled in the CWMU program and require special permits to hunt on them. Consult a good map to ensure you know where you are and to avoid any trespass conflicts
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Piute, Sevier and Wayne counties—Boundary begins at SR-24 and SR-72; west and north on SR-24 to I-70; east on I-70 to SR-72; south on SR-72 to SR-24. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps:  Loa, Salina. Boundary questions? Call the Cedar City office, 435-865-6100.
